    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "*Followup to https://github.com/neovim/neovim/issues/30889*\n\n\n### Problem\n\nA buggy plugin might leave an image and the user has no easy way to clear it. So, similar to highlights and other global state, it's always necessary to provide a fallback that clears resets stuff when something goes wrong.\n\n### Expected behavior\n\n`vim.ui.img.del(nil)` or `vim.ui.img.del(<something>)` clears all images?\n\nIf possible, `vim.ui.img` should avoid managing a bunch of internal state. It should leverage editor concepts like namespaces, extmarks.\n\nIt should also be possible to iterate images, so that things like `:Inspect` can work on images. Maybe that should be a separate issue though.",
    "closed_at": null,
    "closed_by": null,
    "comment_data": [
        {
            "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
            "body": "Kitty's graphics protocol provides a method to delete all visible placements. To me, this is about as close as you can get with absolute graphics. I'm not sure (yet) how this works with the unicode placeholders we'd consider for #39432.\n\nAccording to the protocol, if all placements for an image are deleted, the image itself is also deleted from the terminal. Given the `vim.ui.img` implementation currently just maintains a singular id for both image & placement, I think this is fine.\n\n@kovidgoyal is there any better way to do this? I'm not aware of the kitty graphics protocol providing any way to query for a list of active images; so, it seems like the best approach if we were to support something like this is to clear everything on screen.\n\n@justinmk only other approach I can think of, especially if you wanted to distinguish neovim-created images versus other programs, would be to store a cached list of ids of images created by neovim that you could refer to later.",
